==={{anchor|In games}}Games=== ===={{anchor|In video games}}Video games==== {{main|List of ninja video games}} In addition to video games, several game-development companies use "ninja" in their name: [[Ninja Studio]], [[Ninja Theory]], Ninjaforce, NinjaKiwi,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ninjakiwi.com/ |title=Free Online Games |publisher=Ninja Kiwi |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> and [[Team Ninja]]. In [[massively multiplayer online role-playing game]]s (MMORPGs), "ninja", "loot ninja" or "ninja looter" pejoratively describes a player who has stolen something from another player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/extra/top10ninjasinvideogames.html |title=Top 10 Ninjas In Video Games - Cheat Code Central |publisher=Cheatcc.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-05}}</ref>
===={{anchor|In traditional games}}Traditional games==== Ninja-themed [[role-playing game]]s (RPGs) include: * ''[[Bushido (role-playing game)|Bushido]]'': A role-playing game set in feudal Japan, it includes the supplement ''Ninja&nbsp;– Shadows Over Nippon''. * ''[[Choose Your Own Adventure]]'': There are ninja characters in several [[gamebook]]s in the series: ''Secret of the Ninja'' (#66), ''Return of the Ninja'' (#92), ''The Lost Ninja'' (#113), ''Ninja Cyborg'' (#155) and ''Ninja Avenger'' (#179). * ''[[Feng Shui (role-playing game)|Feng Shui]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlas-games.com/product_tables/AG4011.php |title=Iron & Silk&nbsp;– Atlas Games: Charting New Realms of Imagination |publisher=Atlas Games |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Hero System]]'': Includes the ''Ninja Hero'' gamebook. * ''[[Legend of the Five Rings]]'': Set in a world resembling feudal Japan, it includes the [[sourcebook]] ''Way of the Ninja''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.l5r.com/archive/rpg/products/archive.html |title=Legend of the Five Rings - Roleplaying Game - Products |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2008-10-11 |accessdate=2016-08-12 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011220754/http://www.l5r.com/archive/rpg/products/archive.html |archivedate=2008-10-11 |df= }}</ref> * ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'': [[Ninja (Dungeons & Dragons)|Ninja]] is a [[character class]] first appearing in the 1985 first-edition supplement, ''[[Oriental Adventures]]''. ''Test of the Ninja'' is an ''AD&D'' gamebook. The Ninja class was added to edition 3.5 in ''[[Complete Adventurer]]''. * ''[[Ninja Burger]]'': Three editions and a card game based on the website * ''[[Ninjas and Superspies]]'': Modern setting * ''[[Queen's Blade]]'': Two series of erotic gamebooks featuring the ninja Shizuka and video-game ninja such as Mai Shiranui, [[Kasumi (Dead or Alive)|Kasumi]] and [[Taki (Soulcalibur)|Taki]] in ''[[Queen's Gate]]''. * ''[[Rifts (role-playing game)|Rifts]]'': The Mystic Ninja and Ninja Jucier character classes were introduced in the book, ''Rifts World Book 8: Japan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://palladium-store.com/1001/product/818-Rifts-World-Book-8-Japan.html |title=Palladium Books Store Rifts® World Book 8: Japan |publisher=Palladium-store.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Street Fighter: The Storytelling Game]]'' * ''[[Sengoku (role-playing game)|Sengoku]]'': Samurai game set in 16th-century Japan which includes the sourcebook, ''Shinobi, Shadows of Nihon'' * ''[[Spycraft]]'': Modern espionage game with a ninja character class in the [[campaign setting]] ''World On Fire''<ref>{{cite web |author1=Alex Flagg |author2=Scott Gearin |author3=Patrick Kapera |url=http://www.crafty-games.com/node/81 |title=World on Fire |publisher=Crafty Games |date=2007-12-24 |accessdate=2013-08-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513035239/http://www.crafty-games.com/node/81 |archivedate=2014-05-13 |df= }}</ref> * ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles & Other Strangeness]]'': Game by Palladium Books based on the Ninja Turtles * ''[[The Way of the Tiger]]'': Ninja-themed series of gamebooks, set in a fantasy world
Ninja ara also featured in [[collectible card game]]s such as ''[[Legend of the Five Rings (collectible card game)|Legend of the Five Rings CCG]]'', ''[[Magic: The Gathering]]'' (where the ability Ninjutsu was introduced in the set [[Betrayers of Kamigawa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wizards.com/magic/displaythemedeck.asp?set=bok&decknum=2 |title=Betrayers of Kamigawa Theme Deck&nbsp;– Ninjutsu |publisher=Wizards.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref>) and ''[[Mortal Kombat Kard Game]]'', and in some [[miniature wargaming]] games, such as ''[[Heroscape]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.atomz.com/search/?sp_a=sp10028aa8&sp_t=heroscape&sp_k=Heroscape&sp_q=ninja|title=Heroscape - Search Results|publisher=Search.atomz.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>
==={{anchor|On the Internet|Websites and web comics|Other}}Internet=== Ninja-themed websites include: * ''[[Ask A Ninja]]'': Series of podcasts where a ninja answers questions about ninja * ''Ikenhisu'': Live-action web series<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zeM7I3jEACY|title=Ikenhisu full episodes|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Ninja Burger]]'': Humor website, RPG, card game and book in which ninja run a fast-food delivery service * ''[[Ninja Spirit (video series)|Ninja Spirit]]'': Series of short martial-arts parody videos * ''[[Ninjai|Ninjai: The Little Ninja]]'': Flash animation * ''[[Ninja the Mission Force]]'': Comedy series * ''[[No Need for Bushido]]'': Webcomic * ''One Warm Night'': Web TV series<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC7XHidh5IvBcLPHbhesC9uQ|title=One Warm Night - Original Series|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Pucca]]'': Flash-animated Korean media franchise which includes a book and TV series * ''[[Real Ultimate Power]]'': Humour website created by Robert A. Hamburger, a 13-year-old character * ''[[The Adventures of Dr. McNinja]]'': Webcomic about an Irish doctor ninja obsessed with Batman * ''[[Snafu Comics#TIN The Incompetent Ninja|TIN The Incompetent Ninja]]'': Webcomic series * ''Vexika'': Live-action web series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vexika.com/|title=Vexika|publisher=Vexika.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[White Ninja (webcomic)|White Ninja]]'': Webcomic part of the [[National Lampoon Inc|National Lampoon]] Humor Network * ''Zombies vs. Ninjas'': Web cartoon series by [[Shut Up! Cartoons]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4D8DEC1191107AB8|title=Zombies vs. Ninjas|publisher=Youtube.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>
In information technology, "cyber ninja" are sophisticated counter-hackers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Drew |first=Christopher |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/03/education/edlife/03cybersecurity.html |title=Cybersecurity&nbsp;– Wanted - 'Cyber Ninjas' |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|date=2009-12-29 |accessdate=2010-06-30}}</ref>
==={{anchor|In literature}}Literature=== ===={{anchor|In novels}}Novels==== Ninja-themed novels include: * ''[[American Chillers]]'' and [[Magic Tree House series|''Magic Tree House'' series]]: ''New York Ninjas''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanchillers.com/index.php/cybrary-launch-pages/84-american-chillers-cybrary/97-4-new-york-ninjas|title=#4 New York Ninjas|publisher=Americanchillers.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> and ''Night of the Ninjas'' * ''Brett Wallace: Ninja Master:'' Eight-book series by Wade Barker (Richard Meyers)<ref name=dw>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=3234|title=Vintage Ninja|publisher=Vintageninja.net|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Demon King Daimao]]'': [[Light novel]]s by Shotaro Mizuki, with girls representing the rival Koga and Iga ninja clans; adapted into anime and manga series * ''[[The Diamond Chariot]]'': [[Erast Fandorin]] learns ninjutsu in Japan. * ''[[Fukurō no Shiro]]'' by [[Ryotaro Shiba]], who also wrote a collection of short stories (''Saigo no Igamono'') * ''[[Kage Kara Mamoru!]]:'' Series of light novels adapted into manga and anime series * ''[[The Kouga Ninja Scrolls|The Kouga Ninja Scrolls (Kōga Ninpōchō)]]'': Novel by [[Futaro Yamada]] about two rival ninja clans, the [[Iga-ryū|Iga]] and [[Kōga-ryū|Kouga]]; adapted into manga and anime series and a live-action film * ''Tulku, a Tale of Modern Ninja'': Novel by American ninjutsu practitioner [[Stephen K. Hayes]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Tulku_a_Tale_of_Modern_Ninja.html?id=pvefMQEACAAJ | title= Tulku, a tale of modern Ninja&nbsp;– Stephen K. Hayes| work = Google Books | accessdate = 2012-11-14}}</ref> * ''Kamui'': Series of five novels by [[Tetsu Yano]], later adapted in manga, anime and live-action formats * ''[[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]]'' ([[Serbian language|Serbian]]: ''Ninđa'' or ''Nindža'') was a series of more than 150 [[Pulp magazine|pulp novels]], mostly written by Brana Nikolić alias Derek Finegan, published in [[Yugoslavia]] 1983-1998 * ''Ninja's Revenge'' and ''The Bamboo Bloodbath'' by [[Piers Anthony]]<ref name=dw/> * ''Mirror Friend, Mirror Foe'': Novel by [[Robert Asprin]] and [[George Takei]], featuring a future ninja clan member * ''[[The Ninja (book)|The Ninja]]'': [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]] by [[Eric Van Lustbader]] featuring a half-Japanese, half-white character who received ninjutsu training in his youth; followed by ''The Miko'', ''White Ninja'', ''The Kaisho'', ''Floating City'' and ''Second Skin'' * ''The Ninja Murders'': Historical novel by Andrew B. Suhrer * ''[[Ninja Slayer]]'': Series of Japanese cyberpunk novels by "Bradley Bond",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ninjaslayer.jp/index.html|title=ニンジャスレイヤー書籍公式サイト|publisher=Ninjaslayer.jp|date=|accessdate=2013-11-03|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012142919/http://ninjaslayer.jp/index.html|archivedate=2013-10-12|df=}}</ref> later adapted into manga and anime series * ''Not for Glory'': [[Space opera]] novel by [[Joel Rosenberg (science fiction author)|Joel Rosenberg]] about a mercenary Jewish-Japanese tribe which practices ninjutsu * ''[[Sanada Ten Braves|Sanada Ten Braves (Sanada Jūyūshi)]]:'' [[Meiji period|Meiji]] legend, first published in novel form in 1912 during the [[Taishō period]] * ''[[Shinobi no Mono]]'': Series of novels by [[Tomoyoshi Murayama]] about the life of Ishikawa Goemon. During the 1960s, it was adapted into a series of films about Goemon and other historical ninja. * ''[[Tales of the Otori]]'': The Tribe consists of five ninja families with powers. * ''Tsuma-wa, Kunoichi'': Historical novel<ref>{{cite web|author=原作：風野真知雄 |url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/product/321211000202/ |title=株式会社KADOKAWAオフィシャルサイト｜妻は、くノ一 |publisher=Kadokawa.co.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref>
Ninja have minor roles in ''[[Shōgun (novel)|Shōgun]]'', ''[[Thief of Time]]'', ''[[Vineland]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Beckett | first=Andy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jul/31/thomas-pynchon-vineland-rereading |title=Rereading: Vineland by Thomas Pynchon &#124; Books |publisher=The Guardian |date=2012-11-09 |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref> and the ''[[Young Samurai]]'' series.
===={{anchor|In non-Japanese comics}}Non-Japanese comics==== [[File:Cosplayer of Psylocke 2012-04-24.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Scantily-clad young woman with a sword|[[Psylocke]] cosplayer, 2014]] In the [[Marvel Universe]], ninjas have been heroes and villains. Examples include [[Spider-Man]]'s foe White Ninja, [[X-Men]] members [[Psylocke]], [[Revanche (Marvel Comics)|Revanche]] and supporting character [[Yukio (comics)|Yukio]], [[Ghost Rider]]'s foes [[Deathwatch (comics)|Deathwatch]] and Death Ninja, [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]]'s mentor [[Ogun (Marvel Comics)|Ogun]], [[Hawkeye (comics)|Hawkeye]] (as Ninja Ronin), the [[Punisher]]'s friend Katherine Yakamoto (from [[Shadowmasters]]), and [[Pacific Overlords]] operative Kuroko (Aya Komatsu). In the ''[[Marvel Mangaverse]]'', Spider-Man is the last member of a ninja clan. A sinister ninja cult, [[The Hand (comics)|the Hand]], appears in ''[[X-Men]]'' and ''[[Daredevil (Marvel Comics series)|Daredevil]]''. The cult and its associates were responsible for the martial training of Psylocke, [[Elektra (comics)|Elektra]], Daredevil, [[Black Tarantula]], [[Kitty Pryde]], [[Lady Bullseye]] and Wolverine. The Hand's heroic counterpart is [[The Chaste]], which struggles with its Korean offshoot the True Believers (including Dragonfly Meiko Yin).
Characters with mystical, superhuman martial-arts abilities attributed to ninja appear in the [[DC Universe]]. Bruce Wayne received ninja training prior to becoming Batman. Another character portrayed similarly to a ninja is master martial artist and assassin [[Lady Shiva]]; Shiva killed [[Armless Master]], who trained [[Catwoman]] and [[Hellhound]]. One alternative-universe comic substitutes Batman with a Japanese female ninja named Komori (Bat).<ref>''Justice League of America: Shogun of Steel'' (Elseworlds, 2002).</ref> An [[Alternative versions of Robin|alternative version of Robin]], Tengu, was raised by Cat-Ninja (Catwoman) in feudal Japan. DC's [[The New 52]] introduced Kunoichi, a member of the [[Blackhawks (DC Comics)|Blackhawks]].
In the ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' (TMNT) series, the [[List of Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles characters|main characters and many of their friends and foes]] are ninja, mainly from the [[Foot Clan]] (a pastiche of Marvel's group, the Hand): [[Donatello (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Donatello]], [[Leonardo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Leonardo]], [[Michelangelo (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Michelangelo]], [[Raphael (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Raphael]], [[Splinter (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Splinter]], [[Shredder (Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles)|Shredder]] and [[Karai (character)|Karai]].
The comic version of ''[[G.I. Joe]]'' has featured more ninja than the cartoon series. Story arcs involved [[Scarlett (G.I. Joe)|Scarlett]], [[Snake Eyes (G.I. Joe)|Snake Eyes]], [[Storm Shadow (G.I. Joe)|Storm Shadow]], [[Jinx (G.I. Joe)|Jinx]], [[Kamakura (G.I. Joe)|Kamakura]], [[Firefly (G.I. Joe)|Firefly]] and the [[Arashikage]] ninja clan, an extended family of ninja characters. [[Cobra Commander]]'s son, [[Billy Kessler]], and the shape-shifter [[Zartan]] also received ninja training from the Arashikage clan and their associates.
Other ninja-themed comics include: * ''[[Biotrog]]'' * ''[[Blade for Barter]]'' * ''[[Cowboy Ninja Viking]]'' * ''Half Past Danger''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/2013/05/07/half-past-danger-comic-book-series/2140391/|title='Half Past Danger' is adventure time for Stephen Mooney|author=Brian Truitt|date=7 May 2013|publisher=Usatoday.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Jetta: Tales of the Toshigawa]]'' * ''[[Naruto]]'' * ''[[Kabuki (comics)|Kabuki]]'': Series about a member of a government-backed circle of masked, costumed female assassins in near-future Japan * ''Kyoteru'' * ''[[Mail Order Ninja]]'' * ''[[Mortal Kombat comic books|Mortal Kombat]]'': Series based on the video-game series of the same name with [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]], [[Kitana (Mortal Kombat)|Kitana]], [[Mileena]], [[Reptile (Mortal Kombat)|Reptile]], [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]] and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]] * ''[[Ninja (comic book)|Ninja]]'': Series published from 1986 to 1989 in 40 episodes in [[Yugoslavia]] * ''[[Ninja Boy]]'' * ''[[Ninja Funnies]]'' * ''[[Ninja High School]]'': Ninja-themed, comedy series * ''[[Ninjak]]'' * ''[[Nth Man: The Ultimate Ninja]]'': An American ninja during World War III * ''[[Pirates Vs. Ninjas]]'' * ''Samurai's Blood''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gotham-news.com/news/2011/10/20/erics-image-comics-review-samurais-blood-5|title=Eric's Image Comics Review: SAMURAI'S BLOOD #5|publisher=Gotham-news.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Shi (comics)|Shi]]'': Series about a modern war between descendants of medieval Japanese warrior monks * ''[[Sin City]]'': ''[[Hardboiled|Noir]]'' series with [[Miho (Sin City)|Miho]] * ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turkeys'': [[Dean Rankine]]'s parody of ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'' for ''[[The Beano]]'' * ''Whisper'': Series by [[Steven Grant]] about a modern female ninja.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=2480 |title=WHISPER covers |publisher=Vintage Ninja |