==={{anchor|In sports}}Sports=== Iga F.C. Kunoichi is a Japanese [[L. League]] [[women's association football]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igafc.jp/ |title=伊賀フットボールクラブ くノ一 |publisher=Igafc.jp |date= |accessdate=2013-11-03}}</ref> The [[New Haven Ninjas]] are an [[American football]] team in [[New Haven, Connecticut]]. The American Ninja is the stage name of wrestler [[Brian Adams (wrestler)|Brian Adams]], and the Black Ninja is the stage name of wrestler [[Cocoa Samoa]]. The [[Canadian NINJAs]] are a [[professional wrestling]] [[tag team]]. "Ninja" is a nickname of Brazilian MMA fighter [[Murilo Rua]], and "The Ninja" is the nickname of Filipino boxer [[Bert Batawang]]. Ninja Chops wrestles in the [[Naked Women's Wrestling League]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Julian Cram |url=http://www.dbmagazine.com.au/364/dv-ivNinjaChops.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060205102512/http://www.dbmagazine.com.au/364/dv-ivNinjaChops.shtml |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2006-02-05 |title=dbmagazine au dv ivNinjaChops |publisher=dBmagazine.com.au |date= |accessdate=2010-06-30 |df= }}</ref> Super Ninja is a [[ring name]] of several professional wrestlers, including [[Keiji Mutoh]] and [[Rip Oliver]].
==={{anchor|In television}}Television===
===={{anchor|Television series}}Series==== Non-anime, ninja-themed TV series include: * ''[[American Ninja Warrior]]'' (2009-): Ninja-themed obstacle course show * ''Blood of the Samurai: The Series'' (2004) and ''Ninja EX'' (2004–2005): Indie action series and its spin-off martial-arts comedy series<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninjaex.com/ |title=ninja ex |publisher=ninja ex |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''Bounty Hunter (Shokin Kasegi)'' (1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=111 |title=Judy Ongg as KAGERO |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[G.I. Joe]]'': Four cartoons ([[G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero (1985 TV series)|''G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero'' 1985]] and [[G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero (1989 TV series)|1989]] series, ''[[G.I. Joe Extreme]]'' and ''[[G.I. Joe: Sigma 6]]'') * ''[[Fūma no Kojirō]]'' (2007) * ''Henshin Ninja Arashi'' (1972–1973): Edo-period henshin series based on the manga of the same name * ''[[Kaiketsu Lion-Maru]]'' (1972–1973) and ''[[Fuun Lion-Maru]]'' (1973) * ''Kurama Tengu'': Series running for over a half-century,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www5f.biglobe.ne.jp/~st_octopus/MOVIE/SILENT/25ARAKAN.htm|title=鞍馬天狗見参～嵐寛寿郎と「鞍馬天狗」|publisher=5f.biglobe.ne.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> with nine actors playing the title role as of 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pachinkovista.com/info/news.php?nid=200803191721407n |title=パチンコビスタ（パチビス） パチンコ・パチスロ業界ニュース 藤商事『CR鞍馬天狗』新機種発表会 |publisher=Pachinkovista.com |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref> * ''[[Lego Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]'': Series about six teenage ninja, one of whom is a sentient "nindroid" * ''[[Lone Wolf and Cub|Lone Wolf and Cub/Iron Samurai (Kozure Ōkami)]]'' (1973–1976) * ''Majin Hunter Mitsurugi'': [[Tokusatsu]] series set in the Tokugawa era<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?tag=majin-hunter-mitsurugi |title=Majin Hunter Mitsurugi |publisher=Vintage Ninja |date=2011-10-28 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Akakage|Masked Ninja Red Shadow (Kamen no Ninja Aka-Kage)]]'' (1967–1968): Its footage was used in ''The Magic Sword of Watari''. * ''[[The Master (U.S. TV series)|The Master]]'' (1984): Action-adventure series about John Peter McAllister, an older American veteran and ninja master who returned to the United States * ''Mito Kōmon Gaiden Kagerō Ninpō-chō'' (1995):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kabuki-japan.com/history_E.html|title=The Official Nakamura Hashinosuke Home Page|publisher=Kabuki-japan.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Ninja spinoff of ''[[Mito Kōmon]]'' * ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'': Animated version of the video-game series, with Kitana in a lead role * ''[[Mortal Kombat: Legacy]]'' (2011–) * ''[[Ninja Captor]]'' (1976–1977) * ''Ninpō Kagerō Giri'' (1972)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.jp/%E4%B8%8D%E6%9C%BD%E3%81%AE%E6%99%82%E4%BB%A3%E5%8A%87%E3%83%A9%E3%82%A4%E3%83%96%E3%83%A9%E3%83%AA%E3%83%BC-%E7%AC%AC2%E9%9B%86-%E5%BF%8D%E6%B3%95%E3%81%8B%E3%81%92%E3%82%8D%E3%81%86%E6%96%AC%E3%82%8A-DVD-BOX-1/dp/B00O2Q4U0E|title=不朽の時代劇ライブラリー 第2集 忍法かげろう斬り DVD-BOX 1|publisher=Amazon.jp|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> * ''[[Ōedo Sōsamō]]'' (1970–1992) * ''[[Phantom Agents|Phantom Agents (Ninja Butai Gekkō)]]'' (1964–1966): Action series about a group of ninja agents working for the Japanese government * ''[[Pucca (TV series)|Pucca]]'': A ninja boy, Garu, is the love interest of the series' main character; his nemesis, Tobe, is also a ninja. * ''[[Rambo and the Forces of Freedom]]'': Rambo's ally (White Dragon) and his enemy (Black Dragon) * ''[[Randy Cunningham: 9th Grade Ninja]]'' (2012–2015) * ''[[Raven (U.S. TV series)|Raven]]'' (1993–1994) * ''[[The Samurai (TV series)|The Samurai (Onmitsu Kenshi)]]'' (1962–1965): [[Jidaigeki]] series with Tombei the Mist (an Iga ninja) as the hero's sidekick and many ninja villains * ''[[Samurai Girl (TV miniseries)|Samurai Girl]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|last=Dore |first=Shalini |url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117938190 |title=Variety Reviews&nbsp;– Samurai Girl |publisher=Variety.com |date=2008-09-04 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Sekai Ninja Sen Jiraiya]]'' (1988-1989): Part of [[Toei Company|Toei]]'s ''[[Metal Heroes]]'' [[tokusatsu]] series * ''[[Shadow Warriors (TV series)|Shadow Warriors (Kage no Gundan)]]'' (1980), ''Shadow Warriors II (Kage no Gundan II)'' (1981-1982), ''Shadow Warriors III (Kage no Gundan III)'' (1982), ''Shadow Warriors IV (Kage no Gundan IV)'' (1985) * ''[[Shogun Iemitsu Shinobi Tabi|Shōgun Iemitsu Shinobi Tabi]]'' (1990–1993) * ''[[Shōgun no Onmitsu! Kage Jūhachi]]'' (1996) * ''[[Shuriken School]]'': Cartoon about a ninja school * ''[[Sukeban Deka|Sukeban Deka III: Shōjo Ninpō-chō Denki]]'' (1986–1987) * ''[[Supah Ninjas]]'' (2011–2013) * ''Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'': [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (1987 TV series)|The 1980s]], [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2003 TV series)|the 2000s]] and [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (2012 TV series)|the 2010s]] cartoons and [[Ninja Turtles: The Next Mutation|a live-action TV series]] * ''Tsuma-wa, Kunoichi'' (2014-2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/jidaigeki/kunoichi/ |title=「妻は、くノ一」｜NHKオンライン |publisher=Nhk.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhk.or.jp/jidaigeki/kunoichi2/ |title=BS時代劇「妻は、くノ一 ～最終章～」｜NHKオンライン |publisher=Nhk.or.jp |date= |accessdate=2015-11-06}}</ref>
Ninja-themed [[Super Sentai]] and [[Power Rangers]] shows include ''[[Ninja Sentai Kakuranger]]'', ''[[Ninpuu Sentai Hurricaneger|Ninpū Sentai Hurricaneger]]'' and ''[[Shuriken Sentai Ninninger]]''; footage from ''Kakuranger'' was used in season three of ''[[Mighty Morphin Power Rangers]]'', ''Hurricaneger'' was adapted into ''[[Power Rangers Ninja Storm]]'', and ''Ninninger'' was adapted to ''[[Power Rangers Ninja Steel]]'' and ''[[Power Rangers Super Ninja Steel]]''. Ninja villains appear in other Super Sentai series, such as ''[[GoGo Sentai Boukenger]]'' ([[Negative Syndicate]]'s Dark Shadow clan: Gekkou, Yaiba and Shizuka), ''[[Power Rangers: Operation Overdrive]]'' (Miratrix and other Kamdor henchmen), ''[[Hyakujuu Sentai Gaoranger]]'' (Ninja Org Duke Dorodoro; Onikage in ''[[Power Rangers: Wild Force]]''), ''[[Kyōryū Sentai Zyuranger]]'' (Dora Ninja; Dark Warrior in ''Mighty Morphin Power Rangers'' season one), and ''[[Mahou Sentai Magiranger]]'' (Kirikage).
Ninja characters appeared in the live-action series ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'' ("League of Assassins"), ''[[Baretta]]'' ("The Ninja"), ''[[Big Wolf on Campus]]'' ("Play It Again, Samurai"), ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]'' ("The Way of the Ninja"), ''[[Charmed]]'' ("Awakened"), ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' ("True Night"), ''[[Danger Theatre]]'' ("Lethal Luau"), ''[[Dude, What Would Happen]]'' ("Ninja Slicing"), [[Knight Rider (1982 TV series)|''Knight Rider'' (1982)]] ("Knight of the Rising Sun"), ''[[Kyojuu Tokusou Juspion]]'' (the Five Space Ninjas), [[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]] ("The Assassin"), ''[[Loiter Squad]]'', ''[[Lost Girl]]'' ("Big in Japan"), ''[[Magnum P.I.]]'' ("The Arrow That is Not Aimed"), [[Martial Law (TV series)|Martial Law]] ("Bad Seed") and ("This Shogun For Hire"), ''[[Mito Kōmon]]'' (Tsuge no Tobizaru and Kagerō Ogin), ''[[Mortal Kombat: Konquest]]'' (alternative versions of Kitana, Mileena, Reptile, Scorpion and Sub-Zero), ''[[My Name is Earl]]'' ("Creative Writing"), ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'' ("Touch of Death"), ''[[She Spies]]'' ("Fondles"), ''[[Shōgun (TV miniseries)|Shōgun]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintageninja.net/?p=2848|title=Ninja scenes in SHOGUN|publisher=Vintageninja.net|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> ''[[Simon & Simon]]'' ("Opposites Attack"), ''[[Space Sheriff Shaider]]'' (Girls' Army), ''[[That '70s Show]]'' ("Jackie Moves On"), ''[[The Greatest American Hero]]'' ("Thirty Seconds Over Little Tokyo"), ''[[Gridman the Hyper Agent]]'' (Shinobilar), ''[[Verbotene Liebe]]''.
They appeared in the non-anime cartoon series ''[[The Adventures of Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius]]'' ("Crouching Jimmy, Hidden Sheen"), ''[[Adventures of Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' ("Robo-Ninja"), ''[[The Adventures of Super Mario Bros. 3]]'' ("Sneaky Lying Cheating Giant Ninja Koopas"), ''[[American Dragon: Jake Long]]'' (Huntsman and Rose), ''[[Batman Beyond]]'' (Curaré of the [[League of Assassins]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Fitzpatrick |first=Kevin |url=http://www.ugo.com/tv/silent-killers-curare |title=Curare&nbsp;– The Silent Killers of Film and TV |publisher=UGO.com |date=2011-01-31 |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref>), ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]'' (Kyodai Ken in "Night of the Ninja" and "Day of the Samurai"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsfinestonline.com/WF/batman/btas/bios/ken/ |title=Bios&nbsp;– Kyodai Ken &#124; The World's Finest&nbsp;– Batman: The Animated Series |publisher=Worldsfinestonline.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[Beware the Batman]]'' ("Family" and "Sacrifice"), ''[[Black Dynamite]]'' ("Just Beat It or Jackson Five Across Yo' Eyes"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/videos/black-dynamite/jackson-five-across-yo-eyes-or-just-beat-it/|title='Jackson Five Across Yo' Eyes' or 'Just Beat It' - Black Dynamite on Adult Swim Video|date=24 November 2014|work=Adult Swim|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> ''[[Chop Socky Chooks]]'' (Ninja Chimps),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chopsockychooks.weebly.com/characters.html |title=Chop Socky Chooks&nbsp;– Characters |publisher=Chopsockychooks.weebly.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[Karate Kommandos]]'' (Super Ninja), ''[[Code Monkeys]]'' ("Revenge of Matsui"), ''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]'' (Teen Ninjas), ''[[Conan the Adventurer (animated series)|Conan the Adventurer]]'' ("Shadow Walkers",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conantheadventurer.com/shadow-walkers/ |title=Shadow Walkers |publisher=ConanTheAdventurer.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-03}}</ref> "Dragon's Breath" and "Sword, Sai and Shuriken"), ''[[Danny Phantom]]'' (Bertrand), ''[[Digimon Savers]]'' (Falcomon), ''[[Eon Kid]]'' (Black Beauty and her ninja robot army), ''[[Family Guy]]'' (in "[[Wasted Talent]]" and "[[I Take Thee Quagmire]]"), ''[[Happy Tree Friends]]'' (Generic Tee Ninjas), ''[[Jackie Chan Adventures]]'' (the Shadowkhan), ''[[Johnny Test]]'' (one of Johnny's transformation is Ninja Johnny), ''[[Kim Possible]]'' (the Yamanouchi ninja school), ''[[The Legend of Prince Valiant]]'' ("The Ghost"),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://valarnrow.i8.com/EpisodeSummaries.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503134354/http://valarnrow.i8.com/EpisodeSummaries.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2007-05-03 |title=Episode Summaries |publisher=Valarnrow.i8.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04 |df= }}</ref> ''[[The Legend of Zelda (TV series)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' (Sing), ''[[The Penguins of Madagascar]]'' ("Mental Hen/Siege the Day" and "Street Smarts/Nighty Night Ninja"), ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' ("What a Croc!/Ferb TV"), ''[[Planet Sketch]]'' (Ninja Handyman),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetsketch.com/archive/character_ninja.html |title=Ninja Handyman |publisher=Planet Sketch |date= |accessdate=2013-08-04}}</ref> ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]'' ("Night of the Zinja"),{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} ''[[Robot Chicken]]'', ''[[Road Rovers]]'' ("Let Sleeping Dogs Lie"), ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' ("Samurai versus Ninja"), ''[[The Simpsons]]'' (in "[[The Telltale Head]]" [[Bart Simpson]] disguises as a ninja; in "[[Treehouse of Horror XVIII]]" one of the aliens is dressed as a ninja, in "[[Husbands and Knives]]" the [[Comic Book Guy]] has ninja weapons, and in "[[Yokel Chords]]" Bart plays a spoof [[video game]] with a [[Mileena|female ninja]]), ''[[Skunk Fu]]'' (Ninja Monkeys), ''[[South Park]]'' ("[[Good Times with Weapons]]" and "[[Fantastic Easter Special]]"), ''[[Stroker and Hoop]]'' ("Ninja Worrier" and "Chopping Spree"),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.adultswim.com/stroker-and-hoop/ninja-worrier.html |title=Stroker and Hoop : Ninja Worrier - Adult Swim Gold Episodes |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2016-02-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406064820/http://video.adultswim.com/stroker-and-hoop/ninja-worrier.html |archivedate=April 6, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[Superman: The Animated Series]]'' (Death Fist Ninja), ''[[Teen Titans]]'' (in "Masks", [[Beast Boy]] has a video game "Super Ninja Showdown 8"), ''[[List of Transformers TV series|The Transformers]]'' (Greatshot, Nightbird and [[Prowl (Transformers)|Prowl]]), ''[[The Venture Bros.]]'' (Otaku Senzuri), ''[[Wolverine and the X-Men (TV series)|Wolverine and the X-Men]]'' and ''[[Xiaolin Showdown]]'' (Tubbimura).
